[0.617, "o", "\r\u001b[4mMOUNT\u001b[24m(8)                                                                                                     System Administration                                                                                                     \u001b[4mMOUNT\u001b[24m(8)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     mount - mount a filesystem\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-h\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m-V\u001b[22m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-l\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1mmount -a \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-F\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-O \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptlist\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[24m] \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m|\u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m] \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1mmount --bind\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m--rbind\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m--move \u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1mmount --make-\u001b[22m[\u001b[1mr\u001b[22m]{\u001b[1mshared\u001b[22m|\u001b[1mslave\u001b[22m|\u001b[1mprivate"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[22m|\u001b[1munbindable\u001b[22m} \u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     All files accessible in a Unix system are arranged in one big tree, the file hierarchy, rooted at \u001b[4m/\u001b[24m. These files can be spread out over several devices. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand serves to attach the filesystem found on some device to the big\u001b[m\r\n     file tree. Conversely, the \u001b[1mumount\u001b[22m(8) command will detach it again. The filesystem is used to control how data is stored on the device or provided in a virtual way by network or other services.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The standard form of the \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n        \u001b[1mmount -t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m \u001b[4mdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     This  tells the kernel to attach the filesystem found on \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m (which is of type \u001b[4mtype\u001b[24m) at the directory \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m. The option \u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m is optional. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand is usually able to detect a filesystem. The root permissions are necessary\u001b[m\r\n     to mount a filesystem by default. See section \"Non-superuser mounts\" below for more details. The previous contents (if any) and owner and mode of \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m become invisible, and as long as this filesystem remains mounted, the  pathname  \u001b[4mdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     refers to the root of the filesystem on \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     If only the directory or the device is given, for example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[4m\u001b[22m/dir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     then \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mlooks for a mountpoint (and if not found then for a device) in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file. It’s possible to use the \u001b[1m--target \u001b[22mor \u001b[1m--source \u001b[22moptions to avoid ambiguous interpretation of the given argument. For example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n        \u001b[1mmount --target \u001b[4m\u001b[22m/mountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The same filesystem may be mounted more than once, and in some cases (e.g., network filesystems) the same filesystem may be mounted on the same mountpoint multiple times. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand does not implement any policy to control this\u001b[m\r\n     behavior. All behavior is contr"]
[0.003, "o", "olled by the kernel and it is usually specific to the filesystem driver. The exception is \u001b[1m--all\u001b[22m, in this case already mounted filesystems are ignored (see \u001b[1m--all \u001b[22mbelow for more details).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mListing the mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     The listing mode is maintained for backward compatibility only.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     For more robust and customizable output use \u001b[1mfindmnt\u001b[22m(8), \u001b[1mespecially in your scripts\u001b[22m. Note that control characters in the mountpoint name are replaced with '?'.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The following command lists all mounted filesystems (of type \u001b[4mtype\u001b[24m):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-l\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The option \u001b[1m-l \u001b[22madds labels to this listing. See below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mIndicating the device and filesystem\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     Most devices are indicated by a filename (of a block special device), like \u001b[4m/dev/sda1\u001b[24m, but there are other possibilities. For example, in the case of an NFS mount, \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m may look like \u001b[4mknuth.cwi.nl:/dir\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The  device  names of disk partitions are unstable; hardware reconfiguration, and adding or removing a device can cause changes in names. This is the reason why it’s strongly recommended to use filesystem or partition identifiers like\u001b[m\r\n     UUID or LABEL. Currently supported identifiers (tags):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     LABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n         Human readable filesystem identifier. See also \u001b[1m-L\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     UUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n         Filesystem universally unique identifier. The format of the UUID is usually a series of hex digits separated by hyphens. See also \u001b[1m-U\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
