[0.201, "o", "\u001b[Ko\bo"]
[0.344, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K\u001b[4mMOUNT\u001b[24m(8)                                                                                                     System Administration                                                                                                     \u001b[4mMOUNT\u001b[24m(8)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K     mount - mount a filesystem\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-h\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m-V\u001b[22m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-l\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount -a \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-F\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-O \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptlist\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[24m] \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m|\u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m] \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount --bind\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m--rbind\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m--move \u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount --make-\u001b[22m[\u001b[1mr\u001b[22m]{\u001b[1mshared\u001b[22m|\u001b[1mslave\u001b[22m|\u001b[1mprivate\u001b[22m|\u001b[1munbindable\u001b[22m} \u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[21;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[22;1H\u001b[K     All files accessible in a Unix system are arranged in one big tree, the file hierarchy, rooted at \u001b[4m/\u001b[24m. These files can be spread out over several devices. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand serves to attach the filesystem found on some device to the big\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[23;1H\u001b[K     file tree. Conversely, the \u001b[1mumount\u001b[22m(8) command will detach it again. The filesystem is used to control how data is stored on the device or provided in a virtual way by network or other services.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[24;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[25;1H\u001b[K     The standard form of the \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[26;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[27;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount -t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m \u001b[4mdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[28;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[29;1H\u001b[K     This  tells the kernel to attach the filesystem found on \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m (which is of type \u001b[4mtype\u001b[24m) at the directory \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m. The option \u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m is optional. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand is usually able to detect a filesystem. The root permissions are necessary\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[30;1H\u001b[K     to mount a filesystem by default. See section \"Non-superuser mounts\" below for more details. The previous contents (if any) and owner and mode of \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m become invisible, and as long as this filesystem remains mounted, the  pathname  \u001b[4mdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[31;1H\u001b[K     refers to the root of the filesystem on \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[32;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[33;1H\u001b[K     If only the directory or the device is given, for example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[34;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[35;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[4m\u001b[22m/dir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[36;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[37;1H\u001b[K     then \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mlooks for a mountpoint (and if not found then for a device) in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file. It’s possible to use the \u001b[1m--target \u001b[22mor \u001b[1m--source \u001b[22moptions to avoid ambiguous interpretation of the given argument. For example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[38;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[39;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount --target \u001b[4m\u001b[22m/mountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[40;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[41;1H\u001b[K     The same filesystem may be mounted more than once, and in some cases (e.g., network filesystems) the same filesystem may be mounted on the same mountpoint multiple times. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand does not implement any policy to control this\u001b[m\r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[42;1H\u001b[K     behavior. All behavior is controlled by the kernel and it is usually specific to the filesystem driver. The exception is \u001b[1m--all\u001b[22m, in this case already mounted filesystems are ignored (see \u001b[1m--all \u001b[22mbelow for more details).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[43;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[44;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mListing the mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[45;1H\u001b[K     The listing mode is maintained for backward compatibility only.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[46;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[47;1H\u001b[K     For more robust and customizable output use \u001b[1mfindmnt\u001b[22m(8), \u001b[1mespecially in your scripts\u001b[22m. Note that control characters in the mountpoint name are replaced with '?'.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[48;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[49;1H\u001b[K     The following command lists all mounted filesystems (of type \u001b[4mtype\u001b[24m):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[50;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[51;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-l\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[52;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[53;1H\u001b[K     The option \u001b[1m-l \u001b[22madds labels to this listing. See below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[54;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[55;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mIndicating the device and filesystem\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[56;1H\u001b[K     Most devices are indicated by a filename (of a block special device), like \u001b[4m/dev/sda1\u001b[24m, but there are other possibilities. For example, in the case of an NFS mount, \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m may look like \u001b[4mknuth.cwi.nl:/dir\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[57;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[58;1H\u001b[K     The  device  names of disk partitions are unstable; hardware reconfiguration, and adding or removing a device can cause changes in names. This is the reason why it’s strongly recommended to use filesystem or partition identifiers like\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[59;1H\u001b[K     UUID or LABEL. Currently supported identifiers (tags):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[60;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[61;1H\u001b[K     LABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[62;1H\u001b[K         Human readable filesystem identifier. See also \u001b[1m-L\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[63;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[64;1H\u001b[K     UUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[65;1H\u001b[K         Filesystem universally unique identifier. The format of the UUID is usually a series of hex digits separated by hyphens. See also \u001b[1m-U\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[66;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K\u001b[4mMOUNT\u001b[24m(8)                                                                                                     System Administration                                                                                                     \u001b[4mMOUNT\u001b[24m(8)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K     mount - mount a filesystem\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-h\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m-V\u001b[22m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-l\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount -a \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-F\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m\u001b[01;44;33m-O\u001b[0m\u001b[22m\u001b[24m\u001b[1m \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptlist\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m\u001b[01;44;33m-o\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[24m] \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m|\u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m\u001b[01;44;33m-o\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m] \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount --bind\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m--rbind\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m--move \u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount --make-\u001b[22m[\u001b[1mr\u001b[22m]{\u001b[1mshared\u001b[22m|\u001b[1mslave\u001b[22m|\u001b[1mprivate\u001b[22m|\u001b[1munbindable\u001b[22m} \u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[21;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[22;1H\u001b[K     All files accessible in a Unix system are arranged in one big tree, the file hierarchy, rooted at \u001b[4m/\u001b[24m. These files can be spread out over several devices. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand serves to attach the filesystem found on some device to the big\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[23;1H\u001b[K     file tree. Conversely, the \u001b[1mumount\u001b[22m(8) command will detach it again. The filesystem is used to control how data is stored on the device or provided in a virtual way by network or other services.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[24;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[25;1H\u001b[K     The standard form of the \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[26;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[27;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount -t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m \u001b[4mdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[28;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[29;1H\u001b[K     This  tells the kernel to a"]
[0.004, "o", "ttach the filesystem found on \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m (which is of type \u001b[4mtype\u001b[24m) at the directory \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m. The option \u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m is optional. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand is usually able to detect a filesystem. The root permissions are necessary\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[30;1H\u001b[K     to mount a filesystem by default. See section \"Non-superuser mounts\" below for more details. The previous contents (if any) and owner and mode of \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m become invisible, and as long as this filesystem remains mounted, the  pathname  \u001b[4mdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[31;1H\u001b[K     refers to the root of the filesystem on \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[32;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[33;1H\u001b[K     If only the directory or the device is given, for example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[34;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[35;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[4m\u001b[22m/dir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[36;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[37;1H\u001b[K     then \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mlooks for a mountpoint (and if not found then for a device) in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file. It’s possible to use the \u001b[1m--target \u001b[22mor \u001b[1m--source \u001b[22moptions to avoid ambiguous interpretation of the given argument. For example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[38;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[39;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount --target \u001b[4m\u001b[22m/mountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[40;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[41;1H\u001b[K     The same filesystem may be mounted more than once, and in some cases (e.g., network filesystems) the same filesystem may be mounted on the same mountpoint multiple times. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand does not implement any policy to control this\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[42;1H\u001b[K     behavior. All behavior is controlled by the kernel and it is usually specific to the filesystem driver. The exception is \u001b[1m--all\u001b[22m, in this case already mounted filesystems are ignored (see \u001b[1m--all \u001b[22mbelow for more details).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[43;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[44;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mListing the mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[45;1H\u001b[K     The listing mode is maintained for backward compatibility only.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[46;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[47;1H\u001b[K     For more robust and customizable output use \u001b[1mfindmnt\u001b[22m(8), \u001b[1mespecially in your scripts\u001b[22m. Note that control characters in the mountpoint name are replaced with '?'.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[48;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[49;1H\u001b[K     The following command lists all mounted filesystems (of type \u001b[4mtype\u001b[24m):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[50;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[51;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-l\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[52;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[53;1H\u001b[K     The option \u001b[1m-l \u001b[22madds labels to this listing. See below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[54;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[55;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mIndicating the device and filesystem\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[56;1H\u001b[K     Most devices are indicated by a filename (of a block special device), like \u001b[4m/dev/sda1\u001b[24m, but there are other possibilities. For example, in the case of an NFS mount, \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m may look like \u001b[4mknuth.cwi.nl:/dir\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[57;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[58;1H\u001b[K     The  device  names of disk partitions are unstable; hardware reconfiguration, and adding or removing a device can cause changes in names. This is the reason why it’s strongly recommended to use filesystem or partition identifiers like\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[59;1H\u001b[K     UUID or LABEL. Currently supported identifiers (tags):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[60;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[61;1H\u001b[K     LABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[62;1H\u001b[K         Human readable filesystem identifier. See also \u001b[1m-L\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[63;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[64;1H\u001b[K     UUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[65;1H\u001b[K         Filesystem universally unique identifier. The format of the UUID is usually a series of hex digits separated by hyphens. See also \u001b[1m-U\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[66;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H         Note that \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22muses UUIDs as strings. The UUIDs from the command line or from \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) are not converted to internal binary representation. The string representation of the UUID should be based on lower case characters.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     PARTLABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n         Human readable partition identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     PARTUUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n         Partition universally unique identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It"]
[0.008, "o", "’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     ID=\u001b[4mid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n         Hardware block device ID as generated by udevd. This identifier is usually based on WWN (unique storage identifier) and assigned by the hardware manufacturer. See \u001b[1mls /dev/disk/by-id \u001b[22mfor more details,  this  directory  and  running\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 11 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[3.971, "o", "\r\u001b[K/"]
[0.686, "o", "\u001b[Ku\bu"]
[0.245, "o", "\u001b[Ki\bi"]
[0.140, "o", "\u001b[Kd\bd"]
[0.311, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount -a \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-F\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-O \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptlist\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[24m] \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m|\u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m] \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount --bind\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m--rbind\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m--move \u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount --make-\u001b[22m[\u001b[1mr\u001b[22m]{\u001b[1mshared\u001b[22m|\u001b[1mslave\u001b[22m|\u001b[1mprivate\u001b[22m|\u001b[1munbindable\u001b[22m} \u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K     All files accessible in a Unix system are arranged in one big tree, the file hierarchy, rooted at \u001b[4m/\u001b[24m. These files can be spread out over several devices. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand serves to attach the filesystem found on some device to the big\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K     fi"]
[0.001, "o", "le tree. Conversely, the \u001b[1mumount\u001b[22m(8) command will detach it again. The filesystem is used to control how data is stored on the device or provided in a virtual way by network or other services.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K     The standard form of the \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount -t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m \u001b[4mdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K     This  tells the kernel to attach the filesystem found on \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m (which is of type \u001b[4mtype\u001b[24m) at the directory \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m. The option \u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m is optional. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand is usually able to detect a filesystem. The root permissions are necessary\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[K     to mount a filesystem by default. See section \"Non-superuser mounts\" below for more details. The previous contents (if any) and owner and mode of \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m become invisible, and as long as this filesystem remains mounted, the  pathname  \u001b[4mdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[21;1H\u001b[K     refers to the root of the filesystem on \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[22;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[23;1H\u001b[K     If only the directory or the device is given, for example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[24;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[25;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[4m\u001b[22m/dir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[26;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[27;1H\u001b[K     then \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mlooks for a mountpoint (and if not found then for a device) in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file. It’s possible to use the \u001b[1m--target \u001b[22mor \u001b[1m--source \u001b[22moptions to avoid ambiguous interpretation of the given argument. For example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[28;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[29;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount --target \u001b[4m\u001b[22m/mountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[30;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[31;1H\u001b[K     The same filesystem may be mounted more than once, and in some cases (e.g., network filesystems) the same filesystem may be mounted on the same mountpoint multiple times. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand does not implement any policy to control this\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[32;1H\u001b[K     behavior. All behavior is controlled by the kernel and it is usually specific to the filesystem driver. The exception is \u001b[1m--all\u001b[22m, in this case already mounted filesystems are ignored (see \u001b[1m--all \u001b[22mbelow for more details).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[33;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[34;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mListing the mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[35;1H\u001b[K     The listing mode is maintained for backward compatibility only.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[36;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[37;1H\u001b[K     For more robust and customizable output use \u001b[1mfindmnt\u001b[22m(8), \u001b[1mespecially in your scripts\u001b[22m. Note that control characters in the mountpoint name are replaced with '?'.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[38;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[39;1H\u001b[K     The following command lists all mounted filesystems (of type \u001b[4mtype\u001b[24m):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[40;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[41;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-l\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[42;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[43;1H\u001b[K     The option \u001b[1m-l \u001b[22madds labels to this listing. See below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[44;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[45;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mIndicating the device and filesystem\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[46;1H\u001b[K     Most devices are indicated by a filename (of a block special device), like \u001b[4m/dev/sda1\u001b[24m, but there are other possibilities. For example, in the case of an NFS mount, \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m may look like \u001b[4mknuth.cwi.nl:/dir\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[47;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[48;1H\u001b[K     The  device  names of disk partitions are unstable; hardware reconfiguration, and adding or removing a device can cause changes in names. This is the reason why it’s strongly recommended to use filesystem or partition identifiers like\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[49;1H\u001b[K     UUID or LABEL. Currently supported identifiers (tags):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[50;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[51;1H\u001b[K     LABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[52;1H\u001b[K         Human readable filesystem identifier. See also \u001b[1m-L\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[53;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[54;1H\u001b[K     UUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[55;1H\u001b[K         Filesystem universally unique identifier. The format of the UUID is usually a series of hex digits separated by hyphens. See also \u001b[1m-U\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[56;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[57;1H\u001b[K         Note that \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22muses UUIDs as strings. The UUIDs from the command line or from \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) are not converted to internal binary representation. The string representation of the UUID should be based on lower case characters.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[58;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5"]
[0.003, "o", "9;1H\u001b[K     PARTLABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[60;1H\u001b[K         Human readable partition identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[61;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[62;1H\u001b[K     PARTUUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[63;1H\u001b[K         Partition universally unique identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[64;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[65;1H\u001b[K     ID=\u001b[4mid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[66;1H\u001b[K         Hardware block device ID as generated by udevd. This identifier is usually based on WWN (unique storage identifier) and assigned by the hardware manufacturer. See \u001b[1mls /dev/disk/by-id \u001b[22mfor more details,  this  directory  and  running\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount -a \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-F\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-O \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptlist\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[24m] \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m|\u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-fnrsvw\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mfstype\u001b[24m] \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m \u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount --bind\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m--rbind\u001b[22m|\u001b[1m--move \u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K     \u001b[1mmount --make-\u001b[22m[\u001b[1mr\u001b[22m]{\u001b[1mshared\u001b[22m|\u001b[1mslave\u001b[22m|\u001b[1mprivate\u001b[22m|\u001b[1munbindable\u001b[22m} \u001b[4mmountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K     All files accessible in a Unix system are arranged in one big tree, the file hierarchy, rooted at \u001b[4m/\u001b[24m. These files can be spread out over several devices. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand serves to attach the filesystem found on some device to the big\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K     file tree. Conversely, the \u001b[1mumount\u001b[22m(8) command will detach it again. The filesystem is used to control how data is stored on the device or provided in a virtual way by network or other services.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K     The standard form of the \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount -t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m \u001b[4mdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K     This  tells the kernel to attach the filesystem found on \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m (which is of type \u001b[4mtype\u001b[24m) at the directory \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m. The option \u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m is optional. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand is usually able to detect a filesystem. The root permissions are necessary\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[K     to mount a filesystem by default. See section \"Non-superuser mounts\" below for more details. The previous contents (if any) and owner and mode of \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m become invisible, and as long as this filesystem remains mounted, the  pathname  \u001b[4mdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[21;1H\u001b[K     refers to the root of the filesystem on \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[22;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[23;1H\u001b[K     If only the directory or the device is given, for example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[24;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[25;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[4m\u001b[22m/dir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[26;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[27;1H\u001b[K     then \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mlooks for a mountpoint (and if not found then for a device) in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file. It’s possible to use the \u001b[1m--target \u001b[22mor \u001b[1m--source \u001b[22moptions to avoid ambiguous interpretation of the given argument. For example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[28;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[29;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount --target \u001b[4m\u001b[22m/mountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[30;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[31;1H\u001b[K     The same filesystem may be mounted more than once, and in some cases (e.g., network filesystems) the same filesystem may be mounted on the same mountpoint multiple times. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand does not implement any policy to control this\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[32;1H\u001b[K     behavior. All behavior is controlled by the kernel and it is usually specific to the filesystem driver. The exception is \u001b[1m--all\u001b[22m, in this case already mounted filesystems are ignored (see \u001b[1m--all \u001b[22mbelow for more details).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[33;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[34;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mListing the mounts\u001b[0"]
[0.000, "o", "m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[35;1H\u001b[K     The listing mode is maintained for backward compatibility only.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[36;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[37;1H\u001b[K     For more robust and customizable output use \u001b[1mfindmnt\u001b[22m(8), \u001b[1mespecially in your scripts\u001b[22m. Note that control characters in the mountpoint name are replaced with '?'.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[38;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[39;1H\u001b[K     The following command lists all mounted filesystems (of type \u001b[4mtype\u001b[24m):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[40;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[41;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-l\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[42;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[43;1H\u001b[K     The option \u001b[1m-l \u001b[22madds labels to this listing. See below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[44;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[45;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mIndicating the device and filesystem\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[46;1H\u001b[K     Most devices are indicated by a filename (of a block special device), like \u001b[4m/dev/sda1\u001b[24m, but there are other possibilities. For example, in the case of an NFS mount, \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m may look like \u001b[4mknuth.cwi.nl:/dir\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[47;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[48;1H\u001b[K     The  device  names of disk partitions are unstable; hardware reconfiguration, and adding or removing a device can cause changes in names. This is the reason why it’s strongly recommended to use filesystem or partition identifiers like\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[49;1H\u001b[K     U\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m or LABEL. Currently supported identifiers (tags):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[50;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[51;1H\u001b[K     LABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[52;1H\u001b[K         Human readable filesystem identifier. See also \u001b[1m-L\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[53;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[54;1H\u001b[K     U\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m=\u001b[4mu\u001b[01;44;33muid\u001b[0m\u001b[4m\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[55;1H\u001b[K         Filesystem universally unique identifier. The format of the U\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m is usually a series of hex digits separated by hyphens. See also \u001b[1m-U\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[56;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[57;1H\u001b[K         Note that \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22muses U\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[22ms as strings. The U\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[22ms from the command line or from \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) are not converted to internal binary representation. The string representation of the U\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m should be based on lower case characters.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[58;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[59;1H\u001b[K     PARTLABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[60;1H\u001b[K         Human readable partition identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for G\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[61;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[62;1H\u001b[K     PARTU\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m=\u001b[4mu\u001b[01;44;33muid\u001b[0m\u001b[4m\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[63;1H\u001b[K         Partition universally unique identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for G\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[22m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[64;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[65;1H\u001b[K     ID=\u001b[4mid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[66;1H\u001b[K         Hardware block device ID as generated by udevd. This identifier is usually based on WWN (unique storage identifier) and assigned by the hardware manufacturer. See \u001b[1mls /dev/disk/by-id \u001b[22mfor more details,  this  directory  and  running\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H         udevd is required. This identifier is not recommended for generic use as the identifier is not strictly defined and it depends on udev, udev rules and hardware.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The command \u001b[1mlsblk --fs \u001b[22mprovides an overview of filesystems, LABELs and U\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[22ms on available block devices. The command \u001b[1mblkid -p <device> \u001b[22mprovides details about a filesystem on the specified device.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     Don’t forget that there is no guarantee that U\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0ms and labels are really unique, especially if you move, share or copy the device. Use \u001b[1mlsblk -o +U\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[1m,PARTU\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[1m \u001b[22mto verify that the U\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[22ms are really unique in your system.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The  recommended setup is to use tags (e.g. \u001b[1mU\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m=\u001b[4mu\u001b[01;44;33muid\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[4m\u001b[24m) rather than \u001b[4m/dev/disk/by-{label,u\u001b[01;44;33muid\u001b[0m\u001b[4m\u001b[24m\u001b[4m,id,partu\u001b[01;44;33muid\u001b[0m\u001b[4m\u001b[24m\u001b[4m,partlabel}\u001b[24m udev symlinks in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file. Tag"]
[0.000, "o", "s are more readable, robust and portable. The \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m(8) command internally uses\u001b[m\r\n     udev symlinks, so the use of symlinks in \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m has no advantage over tags. For more details see \u001b[1mlibblkid\u001b[22m(3).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The \u001b[4mproc\u001b[24m filesystem is not associated with a special device, and when mounting it, an arbitrary keyword - for example, \u001b[4mproc\u001b[24m - can be used instead of a device specification. (The customary choice \u001b[4mnone\u001b[24m is less fortunate: the error  mes‐\u001b[m\r\n     sage 'none already mounted' from \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcan be confusing.)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mThe files /etc/fstab, /etc/mtab and /proc/mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     The  file  \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m (see \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5)), may contain lines describing what devices are usually mounted where, using which options. The default location of the \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) file can be overridden with the \u001b[1m--fstab \u001b[4m\u001b[22mpath\u001b[24m command-line option (see\u001b[m\r\n     below for more details).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n        \u001b[1mmount -a \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-O \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptlist\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     (usually given in a bootscript) causes all filesystems mentioned in \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m (of the proper type and/or having or not having the proper options) to be mounted as indicated, except for those whose line contains the \u001b[1mnoauto \u001b[22mkeyword.  Adding\u001b[m\r\n     the \u001b[1m-F \u001b[22moption will make \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mfork, so that the filesystems are mounted in parallel.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     When mounting a filesystem mentioned in \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m, it suffices to specify on the command line only the device, or only the mount point.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The  programs  \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mand \u001b[1mumount\u001b[22m(8) traditionally maintained a list of currently mounted filesystems in the file \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m. The support for regular classic \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m is completely disabled at compile time by default, because on current\u001b[m\r\n     Linux systems it is better to make \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m a symlink to \u001b[4m/proc/mounts\u001b[24m instead. The regular \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m file maintained in userspace cannot reliably work with namespaces, containers and other advanced Linux features. If the regular \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m sup‐\u001b[m\r\n     port is enabled, then it’s possible to use the file as well as the symlink.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     If no arguments are given to \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m, the list of mounted filesystems is printed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     If you want to override mount options from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m, you have to use the \u001b[1m-o \u001b[22moption:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[4m\u001b[22mdevice\u001b[24m|\u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m \u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     and then the mount options from the command line will be appended to the list of options from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m. This default behaviour can be changed using the \u001b[1m--options-mode \u001b[22mcommand-line option. The usual behavior is that the  last  option\u001b[m\r\n     wins if there are conflicting ones.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mprogram does not read the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file if both \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m (or LABEL, U\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[24m\u001b[4m\u001b[24m, ID, PARTU\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[24m\u001b[4m\u001b[24m or PARTLABEL) and \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m are specified. For example, to mount device \u001b[1mfoo \u001b[22mat \u001b[1m/dir\u001b[22m:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n        \u001b[1mmount /dev/foo /dir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     This default behaviour can be changed by using the \u001b[1m--options-source-force \u001b[22mcommand-line option to always read configuration from \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m. For non-root users \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22malways reads the \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m configuration.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mNon-superuser mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     Normally, only the superuser can mount filesystems. However, when \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m contains the \u001b[1muser \u001b[22moption on a line, anybody can mount the corresponding filesystem.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     Thus, given a line\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 59 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[5.677, "o", "\r\u001b[K/"]
[0.358, "o", "\u001b[Ku\bu"]
[0.155, "o", "\u001b[Ki\bi"]
[0.120, "o", "\u001b[Kd\bd"]
[0.688, "o", "\u001b[K=\b="]
[0.321, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K     UUID or LABEL. Currently supported identifiers (tags):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K     LABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K         Human readable filesystem identifier. See also \u001b[1m-L\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K     UUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K         Filesystem universally unique identifier. The format of the UUID is usually a series of hex digits separated by hyphens. See also \u001b[1m-U\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K         Note that \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22muses UUIDs as strings. The UUIDs from the command line or from \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) are not converted to internal binary representation. The string representation of the UUID should be based on lower case characters.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K     PARTLABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K         Human readable partition identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K     PARTUUID=\u001b[4muui"]
[0.002, "o", "d\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K         Partition universally unique identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K     ID=\u001b[4mid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K         Hardware block device ID as generated by udevd. This identifier is usually based on WWN (unique storage identifier) and assigned by the hardware manufacturer. See \u001b[1mls /dev/disk/by-id \u001b[22mfor more details,  this  directory  and  running\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K         udevd is required. This identifier is not recommended for generic use as the identifier is not strictly defined and it depends on udev, udev rules and hardware.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[21;1H\u001b[K     The command \u001b[1mlsblk --fs \u001b[22mprovides an overview of filesystems, LABELs and UUIDs on available block devices. The command \u001b[1mblkid -p <device> \u001b[22mprovides details about a filesystem on the specified device.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[22;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[23;1H\u001b[K     Don’t forget that there is no guarantee that UUIDs and labels are really unique, especially if you move, share or copy the device. Use \u001b[1mlsblk -o +UUID,PARTUUID \u001b[22mto verify that the UUIDs are really unique in your system.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[24;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[25;1H\u001b[K     The  recommended setup is to use tags (e.g. \u001b[1mUUID\u001b[22m=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[24m) rather than \u001b[4m/dev/disk/by-{label,uuid,id,partuuid,partlabel}\u001b[24m udev symlinks in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file. Tags are more readable, robust and portable. The \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m(8) command internally uses\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[26;1H\u001b[K     udev symlinks, so the use of symlinks in \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m has no advantage over tags. For more details see \u001b[1mlibblkid\u001b[22m(3).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[27;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[28;1H\u001b[K     The \u001b[4mproc\u001b[24m filesystem is not associated with a special device, and when mounting it, an arbitrary keyword - for example, \u001b[4mproc\u001b[24m - can be used instead of a device specification. (The customary choice \u001b[4mnone\u001b[24m is less fortunate: the error  mes‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[29;1H\u001b[K     sage 'none already mounted' from \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcan be confusing.)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[30;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[31;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mThe files /etc/fstab, /etc/mtab and /proc/mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[32;1H\u001b[K     The  file  \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m (see \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5)), may contain lines describing what devices are usually mounted where, using which options. The default location of the \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) file can be overridden with the \u001b[1m--fstab \u001b[4m\u001b[22mpath\u001b[24m command-line option (see\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[33;1H\u001b[K     below for more details).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[34;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[35;1H\u001b[K     The command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[36;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[37;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount -a \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-O \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptlist\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[38;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[39;1H\u001b[K     (usually given in a bootscript) causes all filesystems mentioned in \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m (of the proper type and/or having or not having the proper options) to be mounted as indicated, except for those whose line contains the \u001b[1mnoauto \u001b[22mkeyword.  Adding\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[40;1H\u001b[K     the \u001b[1m-F \u001b[22moption will make \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mfork, so that the filesystems are mounted in parallel.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[41;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[42;1H\u001b[K     When mounting a filesystem mentioned in \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m, it suffices to specify on the command line only the device, or only the mount point.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[43;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[44;1H\u001b[K     The  programs  \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mand \u001b[1mumount\u001b[22m(8) traditionally maintained a list of currently mounted filesystems in the file \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m. The support for regular classic \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m is completely disabled at compile time by default, because on current\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[45;1H\u001b[K     Linux systems it is better to make \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m a symlink to \u001b[4m/proc/mounts\u001b[24m instead. The regular \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m file maintained in userspace cannot reliably work with namespaces, containers and other advanced Linux features. If the regular \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m sup‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[46;1H\u001b[K     port is enabled, then it’s possible to use the file as well as the symlink.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[47;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[48;1H\u001b[K     If no arguments are given to \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m, the list of mounted filesyste"]
[0.002, "o", "ms is printed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[49;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[50;1H\u001b[K     If you want to override mount options from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m, you have to use the \u001b[1m-o \u001b[22moption:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[51;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[52;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[4m\u001b[22mdevice\u001b[24m|\u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m \u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[53;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[54;1H\u001b[K     and then the mount options from the command line will be appended to the list of options from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m. This default behaviour can be changed using the \u001b[1m--options-mode \u001b[22mcommand-line option. The usual behavior is that the  last  option\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[55;1H\u001b[K     wins if there are conflicting ones.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[56;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[57;1H\u001b[K     The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mprogram does not read the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file if both \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m (or LABEL, UUID, ID, PARTUUID or PARTLABEL) and \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m are specified. For example, to mount device \u001b[1mfoo \u001b[22mat \u001b[1m/dir\u001b[22m:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[58;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[59;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount /dev/foo /dir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[60;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[61;1H\u001b[K     This default behaviour can be changed by using the \u001b[1m--options-source-force \u001b[22mcommand-line option to always read configuration from \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m. For non-root users \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22malways reads the \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m configuration.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[62;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[63;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mNon-superuser mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[64;1H\u001b[K     Normally, only the superuser can mount filesystems. However, when \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m contains the \u001b[1muser \u001b[22moption on a line, anybody can mount the corresponding filesystem.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[65;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[66;1H\u001b[K     Thus, given a line\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K     UUID or LABEL. Currently supported identifiers (tags):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K     LABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K         Human readable filesystem identifier. See also \u001b[1m-L\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K     U\u001b[01;44;33mUID=\u001b[0m\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K         Filesystem universally unique identifier. The format of the UUID is usually a series of hex digits separated by hyphens. See also \u001b[1m-U\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K         Note that \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22muses UUIDs as strings. The UUIDs from the command line or from \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) are not converted to internal binary representation. The string representation of the UUID should be based on lower case characters.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K     PARTLABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K         Human readable partition identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K     PARTU\u001b[01;44;33mUID=\u001b[0m\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K         Partition universally unique identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K     ID=\u001b[4mid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K         Hardware block device ID as generated by udevd. This identifier is usually based on WWN (unique storage identifier) and assigned by the hardware manufacturer. See \u001b[1mls /dev/disk/by-id \u001b[22mfor more details,  this  directory  and  running\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K         udevd is required. This identifier is not recommended for generic use as the identifier is not strictly defined and it depends on udev, udev rules and hardware.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[21;1H\u001b[K     The command \u001b[1mlsblk --fs \u001b[22mprovides an overview of filesystems, LABELs and UUIDs on available block devices. The command \u001b[1mblkid -p <device> \u001b[22mprovides details about a filesystem on the specified device.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[22;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[23;1H\u001b[K     Don’t forget that there is no guarantee that UUIDs and labels are really unique, especially if you move, share or copy the device. Use \u001b[1mlsblk -o +UUID,PARTUUID \u001b[22mto verify that the UUIDs are really unique in your system.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[24;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[25;1H\u001b[K     The  recommended setup is to use tags (e.g. \u001b[1mU\u001b[01;44;33mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[01;44;33m=\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[22m\u001b[4muuid\u001b[24m) rather than \u001b[4m/dev/disk/by-{label,uuid,id,partuuid,partlabel}\u001b[24m udev symlinks in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m"]
[0.002, "o", " file. Tags are more readable, robust and portable. The \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m(8) command internally uses\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[26;1H\u001b[K     udev symlinks, so the use of symlinks in \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m has no advantage over tags. For more details see \u001b[1mlibblkid\u001b[22m(3).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[27;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[28;1H\u001b[K     The \u001b[4mproc\u001b[24m filesystem is not associated with a special device, and when mounting it, an arbitrary keyword - for example, \u001b[4mproc\u001b[24m - can be used instead of a device specification. (The customary choice \u001b[4mnone\u001b[24m is less fortunate: the error  mes‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[29;1H\u001b[K     sage 'none already mounted' from \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcan be confusing.)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[30;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[31;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mThe files /etc/fstab, /etc/mtab and /proc/mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[32;1H\u001b[K     The  file  \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m (see \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5)), may contain lines describing what devices are usually mounted where, using which options. The default location of the \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) file can be overridden with the \u001b[1m--fstab \u001b[4m\u001b[22mpath\u001b[24m command-line option (see\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[33;1H\u001b[K     below for more details).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[34;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[35;1H\u001b[K     The command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[36;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[37;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount -a \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-O \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptlist\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[38;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[39;1H\u001b[K     (usually given in a bootscript) causes all filesystems mentioned in \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m (of the proper type and/or having or not having the proper options) to be mounted as indicated, except for those whose line contains the \u001b[1mnoauto \u001b[22mkeyword.  Adding\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[40;1H\u001b[K     the \u001b[1m-F \u001b[22moption will make \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mfork, so that the filesystems are mounted in parallel.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[41;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[42;1H\u001b[K     When mounting a filesystem mentioned in \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m, it suffices to specify on the command line only the device, or only the mount point.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[43;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[44;1H\u001b[K     The  programs  \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mand \u001b[1mumount\u001b[22m(8) traditionally maintained a list of currently mounted filesystems in the file \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m. The support for regular classic \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m is completely disabled at compile time by default, because on current\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[45;1H\u001b[K     Linux systems it is better to make \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m a symlink to \u001b[4m/proc/mounts\u001b[24m instead. The regular \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m file maintained in userspace cannot reliably work with namespaces, containers and other advanced Linux features. If the regular \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m sup‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[46;1H\u001b[K     port is enabled, then it’s possible to use the file as well as the symlink.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[47;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[48;1H\u001b[K     If no arguments are given to \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m, the list of mounted filesystems is printed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[49;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[50;1H\u001b[K     If you want to override mount options from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m, you have to use the \u001b[1m-o \u001b[22moption:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[51;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[52;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[4m\u001b[22mdevice\u001b[24m|\u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m \u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[53;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[54;1H\u001b[K     and then the mount options from the command line will be appended to the list of options from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m. This default behaviour can be changed using the \u001b[1m--options-mode \u001b[22mcommand-line option. The usual behavior is that the  last  option\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[55;1H\u001b[K     wins if there are conflicting ones.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[56;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[57;1H\u001b[K     The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mprogram does not read the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file if both \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m (or LABEL, UUID, ID, PARTUUID or PARTLABEL) and \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m are specified. For example, to mount device \u001b[1mfoo \u001b[22mat \u001b[1m/dir\u001b[22m:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[58;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[59;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount /dev/foo /dir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[60;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[61;1H\u001b[K     This default behaviour can be changed by using the \u001b[1m--options-source-force \u001b[22mcommand-line option to always read configuration from \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m. For non-root users \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22malways reads the \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m configuration.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[62;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[63;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mNon-superuser mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[64;1H\u001b[K     Normally, only the superuser can mount filesystems. However, when \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m contains the \u001b[1muser \u001b[22moption on a line, anybody can mount the corresponding filesystem.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[65;1H\u001b"]
[0.000, "o", "[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[66;1H\u001b[K     Thus, given a line\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\u001b[m\r\n        \u001b[1m/dev/cdrom /cd iso9660 ro,user,noauto,unhide\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     any user can mount the iso9660 filesystem found on an inserted CDROM using the command:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 64 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[4.335, "o", "\r\u001b[K/"]
[1.666, "o", "\u001b[K-\b-"]
[0.226, "o", "\u001b[Ko\bo"]
[0.185, "o", "\u001b[K \b "]
[0.436, "o", "\u001b[Ku\bu"]
[0.202, "o", "\u001b[Ki\bi"]
[0.171, "o", "\u001b[Kd\bd"]
[0.255, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K     UUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K         Filesystem universally unique identifier. The format of the UUID is usually a series of hex digits separated by hyphens. See also \u001b[1m-U\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K         Note that \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22muses UUIDs as strings. The UUIDs from the command line or from \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) are not converted to internal binary representation. The string representation of the UUID should be based on lower case characters.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K     PARTLABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K         Human readable partition identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K     PARTUUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K         Partition universally unique identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID P"]
[0.001, "o", "artition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K     ID=\u001b[4mid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K         Hardware block device ID as generated by udevd. This identifier is usually based on WWN (unique storage identifier) and assigned by the hardware manufacturer. See \u001b[1mls /dev/disk/by-id \u001b[22mfor more details,  this  directory  and  running\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K         udevd is required. This identifier is not recommended for generic use as the identifier is not strictly defined and it depends on udev, udev rules and hardware.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H\u001b[K     The command \u001b[1mlsblk --fs \u001b[22mprovides an overview of filesystems, LABELs and UUIDs on available block devices. The command \u001b[1mblkid -p <device> \u001b[22mprovides details about a filesystem on the specified device.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K     Don’t forget that there is no guarantee that UUIDs and labels are really unique, especially if you move, share or copy the device. Use \u001b[1mlsblk -o +UUID,PARTUUID \u001b[22mto verify that the UUIDs are really unique in your system.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[K     The  recommended setup is to use tags (e.g. \u001b[1mUUID\u001b[22m=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[24m) rather than \u001b[4m/dev/disk/by-{label,uuid,id,partuuid,partlabel}\u001b[24m udev symlinks in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file. Tags are more readable, robust and portable. The \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m(8) command internally uses\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[21;1H\u001b[K     udev symlinks, so the use of symlinks in \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m has no advantage over tags. For more details see \u001b[1mlibblkid\u001b[22m(3).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[22;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[23;1H\u001b[K     The \u001b[4mproc\u001b[24m filesystem is not associated with a special device, and when mounting it, an arbitrary keyword - for example, \u001b[4mproc\u001b[24m - can be used instead of a device specification. (The customary choice \u001b[4mnone\u001b[24m is less fortunate: the error  mes‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[24;1H\u001b[K     sage 'none already mounted' from \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcan be confusing.)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[25;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[26;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mThe files /etc/fstab, /etc/mtab and /proc/mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[27;1H\u001b[K     The  file  \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m (see \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5)), may contain lines describing what devices are usually mounted where, using which options. The default location of the \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) file can be overridden with the \u001b[1m--fstab \u001b[4m\u001b[22mpath\u001b[24m command-line option (see\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[28;1H\u001b[K     below for more details).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[29;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[30;1H\u001b[K     The command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[31;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[32;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount -a \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-O \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptlist\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[33;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[34;1H\u001b[K     (usually given in a bootscript) causes all filesystems mentioned in \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m (of the proper type and/or having or not having the proper options) to be mounted as indicated, except for those whose line contains the \u001b[1mnoauto \u001b[22mkeyword.  Adding\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[35;1H\u001b[K     the \u001b[1m-F \u001b[22moption will make \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mfork, so that the filesystems are mounted in parallel.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[36;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[37;1H\u001b[K     When mounting a filesystem mentioned in \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m, it suffices to specify on the command line only the device, or only the mount point.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[38;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[39;1H\u001b"]
[0.002, "o", "[K     The  programs  \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mand \u001b[1mumount\u001b[22m(8) traditionally maintained a list of currently mounted filesystems in the file \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m. The support for regular classic \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m is completely disabled at compile time by default, because on current\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[40;1H\u001b[K     Linux systems it is better to make \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m a symlink to \u001b[4m/proc/mounts\u001b[24m instead. The regular \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m file maintained in userspace cannot reliably work with namespaces, containers and other advanced Linux features. If the regular \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m sup‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[41;1H\u001b[K     port is enabled, then it’s possible to use the file as well as the symlink.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[42;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[43;1H\u001b[K     If no arguments are given to \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m, the list of mounted filesystems is printed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[44;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[45;1H\u001b[K     If you want to override mount options from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m, you have to use the \u001b[1m-o \u001b[22moption:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[46;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[47;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[4m\u001b[22mdevice\u001b[24m|\u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m \u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[48;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[49;1H\u001b[K     and then the mount options from the command line will be appended to the list of options from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m. This default behaviour can be changed using the \u001b[1m--options-mode \u001b[22mcommand-line option. The usual behavior is that the  last  option\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[50;1H\u001b[K     wins if there are conflicting ones.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[51;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[52;1H\u001b[K     The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mprogram does not read the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file if both \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m (or LABEL, UUID, ID, PARTUUID or PARTLABEL) and \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m are specified. For example, to mount device \u001b[1mfoo \u001b[22mat \u001b[1m/dir\u001b[22m:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[53;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[54;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount /dev/foo /dir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[55;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[56;1H\u001b[K     This default behaviour can be changed by using the \u001b[1m--options-source-force \u001b[22mcommand-line option to always read configuration from \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m. For non-root users \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22malways reads the \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m configuration.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[57;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[58;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mNon-superuser mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[59;1H\u001b[K     Normally, only the superuser can mount filesystems. However, when \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m contains the \u001b[1muser \u001b[22moption on a line, anybody can mount the corresponding filesystem.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[60;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[61;1H\u001b[K     Thus, given a line\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[62;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[63;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1m/dev/cdrom /cd iso9660 ro,user,noauto,unhide\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[64;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[65;1H\u001b[K     any user can mount the iso9660 filesystem found on an inserted CDROM using the command:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[66;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\u001b[1;1H\u001b[K     UUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[K         Filesystem universally unique identifier. The format of the UUID is usually a series of hex digits separated by hyphens. See also \u001b[1m-U\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[K         Note that \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22muses UUIDs as strings. The UUIDs from the command line or from \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) are not converted to internal binary representation. The string representation of the UUID should be based on lower case characters.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[K     PARTLABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[K         Human readable partition identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H\u001b[K     PARTUUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H\u001b[K         Partition universally unique identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[K     ID=\u001b[4mid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H\u001b[K         Hardware block device ID as generated by udevd. This identifier is usually based on WWN (unique storage identifier) and assigned by the hardware manufacturer. See \u001b[1mls /dev/disk/by-id \u001b[22mfor more details,  this  directory  and  running\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H\u001b[K         udevd is required. This identifier is not recommended for generic use as the identifier is not strictly defined and it depends on udev, udev rules and hardware.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;"]
[0.000, "o", "1H\u001b[K     The command \u001b[1mlsblk --fs \u001b[22mprovides an overview of filesystems, LABELs and UUIDs on available block devices. The command \u001b[1mblkid -p <device> \u001b[22mprovides details about a filesystem on the specified device.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K     Don’t forget that there is no guarantee that UUIDs and labels are really unique, especially if you move, share or copy the device. Use \u001b[1mlsblk -o +UUID,PARTUUID \u001b[22mto verify that the UUIDs are really unique in your system.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[20;1H\u001b[K     The  recommended setup is to use tags (e.g. \u001b[1mUUID\u001b[22m=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[24m) rather than \u001b[4m/dev/disk/by-{label,uuid,id,partuuid,partlabel}\u001b[24m udev symlinks in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file. Tags are more readable, robust and portable. The \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m(8) command internally uses\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[21;1H\u001b[K     udev symlinks, so the use of symlinks in \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m has no advantage over tags. For more details see \u001b[1mlibblkid\u001b[22m(3).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[22;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[23;1H\u001b[K     The \u001b[4mproc\u001b[24m filesystem is not associated with a special device, and when mounting it, an arbitrary keyword - for example, \u001b[4mproc\u001b[24m - can be used instead of a device specification. (The customary choice \u001b[4mnone\u001b[24m is less fortunate: the error  mes‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[24;1H\u001b[K     sage 'none already mounted' from \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcan be confusing.)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[25;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[26;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mThe files /etc/fstab, /etc/mtab and /proc/mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[27;1H\u001b[K     The  file  \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m (see \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5)), may contain lines describing what devices are usually mounted where, using which options. The default location of the \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) file can be overridden with the \u001b[1m--fstab \u001b[4m\u001b[22mpath\u001b[24m command-line option (see\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[28;1H\u001b[K     below for more details).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[29;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[30;1H\u001b[K     The command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[31;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[32;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount -a \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-O \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptlist\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[33;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[34;1H\u001b[K     (usually given in a bootscript) causes all filesystems mentioned in \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m (of the proper type and/or having or not having the proper options) to be mounted as indicated, except for those whose line contains the \u001b[1mnoauto \u001b[22mkeyword.  Adding\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[35;1H\u001b[K     the \u001b[1m-F \u001b[22moption will make \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mfork, so that the filesystems are mounted in parallel.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[36;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[37;1H\u001b[K     When mounting a filesystem mentioned in \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m, it suffices to specify on the command line only the device, or only the mount point.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[38;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[39;1H\u001b[K     The  programs  \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mand \u001b[1mumount\u001b[22m(8) traditionally maintained a list of currently mounted filesystems in the file \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m. The support for regular classic \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m is completely disabled at compile time by default, because on current\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[40;1H\u001b[K     Linux systems it is better to make \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m a symlink to \u001b[4m/proc/mounts\u001b[24m instead. The regular \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m file maintained in userspace cannot reliably work with namespaces, containers and other advanced Linux features. If the regular \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m sup‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[41;1H\u001b[K     port is enabled, then it’s possible to use the file as well as the symlink.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[42;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[43;1H\u001b[K     If no arguments are given to \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m, the list of mounted filesystems is printed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[44;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[45;1H\u001b[K     If you want to override mount options from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m, you have to use the \u001b[1m-o \u001b[22moption:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[46;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[47;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[4m\u001b[22mdevice\u001b[24m|\u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m \u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[48;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[49;1H\u001b[K     and then the mount options from the command line will be appended to the list of options from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m. This default behaviour can be changed using the \u001b[1m--options-mode \u001b[22mcommand-line option. The usual behavior is that the  last  option\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[50;1H\u001b[K     wins if there are conflicting ones.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[51;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[52;1H\u001b[K     The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mprogram does not read the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file if both \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m (or LABEL, UUID, ID, PARTUUID or PARTLABEL) and \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m are specified. For example, to mount device \u001b[1mfoo \u001b[22mat \u001b[1m/dir\u001b[22m:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[53;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[54;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount /dev/foo /dir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[55;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[56;1H\u001b[K     This default behaviour can be changed by using the \u001b[1m--options-source-force \u001b[22mcommand-line option to always read configuration from \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m. For non-root users \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22malways reads the \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m configuration.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[57;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[58;1H\u001b[K   \u001b[1mNon-superuser mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[59;1H\u001b[K     Normally, only the superuser can mount filesystems. However, when \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m contains the \u001b[1muser \u001b[22moption on a line, anybody can mount the corresponding filesystem.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[60;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[61;1H\u001b[K     Thus, given a line\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[62;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[63;1H\u001b[K        \u001b[1m/dev/cdrom /cd iso9660 ro,user,noauto,unhide\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[64;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[65;1H\u001b[K     any user can mount the iso9660 filesystem found on an inserted CDROM using the command:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[66;1H\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H"]
[0.005, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33mPattern not found  (press RETURN)\u001b[0m"]
[2.178, "o", "\u001b[67;1H\u001b[K\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.002, "o", "        \u001b[1mmount /cd\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 65/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.253, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 66/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     Note  that  \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mis very strict about non-root users and all paths specified on command line are verified before \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m is parsed or a helper program is executed. It’s strongly recommended to use a valid mountpoint to specify filesys‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 67/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     tem, otherwise \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mmay fail. For example it’s a bad idea to use NFS or CIFS source on command line.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 68/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 69/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     Since util-linux 2.35, \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mdoes not exit when user permissions are inadequate according to libmount’s internal security rules. Instead, it drops suid permissions and  continues  as  regular  non-root  user.  This  behavior  supports\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 70/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.036, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     use-cases where root permissions are not necessary (e.g., fuse filesystems, user namespaces, etc).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 71/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 72/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "     For  more details, see \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5). Only the user that mounted a filesystem can unmount it again. If any user should be able to unmount it, then use \u001b[1musers \u001b[22minstead of \u001b[1muser \u001b[22min the \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m line. The \u001b[1mowner \u001b[22moption is similar to the \u001b[1muser \u001b[22moption,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 73/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "     with the restriction that the user must be the owner of the special file. This may be useful e.g. for \u001b[4m/dev/fd\u001b[24m if a login script makes the console user owner of this device. The \u001b[1mgroup \u001b[22moption is similar, with the  restriction  that  the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 74/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     user must be a member of the group of the special file.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 75/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 76/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     The  \u001b[1muser  \u001b[22mmount  option  is accepted if no username is specified. If used in the format \u001b[1muser=someone\u001b[22m, the option is silently ignored and visible only for external mount helpers (/sbin/mount.<type>) for compatibility with some network\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 77/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K     filesystems.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 78/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 79/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "   \u001b[1mBind mount operation\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 80/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K     Remount part of the file hierarchy somewhere else. The call is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 81/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 82/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "        \u001b[1mmount --bind \u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 83/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 84/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     or by using this \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m entry:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 85/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 86/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "        \u001b[1m/\u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[1m/\u001b[4m\u001b[22mnewdir\u001b[24m \u001b[1mnone bind\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 87/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 88/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "     After this call the same contents are accessible in two places.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 89/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 90/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "     It is important to understand that \"bind\" does not create any second-class or special node in the kernel VFS. The \"bind\" is just another operation to attach a filesystem. There is nowhere stored information  that  the  filesystem  has\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 91/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "     been attached by a \"bind\" operation. The \u001b[4molddir\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[24m are independent and the \u001b[4molddir\u001b[24m may be unmounted.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 92/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.036, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 93/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     One can also remount a single file (on a single file). It’s also possible to use a bind mount to create a mountpoint from a regular directory, for example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 94/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 95/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.027, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "        \u001b[1mmount --bind foo foo\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 96/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.033, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 97/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "     The bind mount call attaches only (part of) a single filesystem, not possible submounts. The entire file hierarchy including submounts can be attached a second place by using:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 98/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.027, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 99/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "        \u001b[1mmount --rbind \u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 100/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 101/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.130, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "     Note  that the filesystem mount options maintained by the kernel will remain the same as those on the original mount point. The userspace mount options (e.g., _netdev) will not be copied by \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mand it’s necessary to explicitly spec‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 102/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.454, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "     ify the options on the \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand line.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 103/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.257, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 104/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "     Since util-linux 2.27 \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mpermits changing the mount options by passing the relevant options along with \u001b[1m--bind\u001b[22m. For example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 105/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.028, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 106/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "        \u001b[1mmount -o bind,ro foo foo\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 107/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 108/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "     This feature is not supported by the Linux kernel; it is implemented in userspace by an additional \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m(2) remounting system call. This solution is not atomic.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 109/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 110/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     The alternative (classic) way to create a read-only bind mount is to use the remount operation, for example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 111/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.035, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 112/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "        \u001b[1mmount --bind \u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 113/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 114/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "        \u001b[1mmount -o remount,bind,ro \u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 115/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 116/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     Note that a read-only bind will create a read-only mountpoint (VFS entry), but the original filesystem superblock will still be writable, meaning that the \u001b[4molddir\u001b[24m will be writable, but the \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[24m will be read-only.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 117/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 118/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     It’s also possible to change nosuid, nodev, noexec, noatime, nodiratime, relatime and nosymfollow VFS entry flags via a \"remount,bind\" operation. The other flags (for example filesystem-specific flags) are silently ignored. The  clas‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 119/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.357, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     sic  \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m(2)  system  call  does  not  allow to change mount options recursively (for example with \u001b[1m-o rbind,ro\u001b[22m). The recursive semantic is possible with a new \u001b[1mmount_setattr\u001b[22m(2) kernel system call and it’s supported since libmount from\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 120/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.256, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     util-linux v2.39 by a new experimental \"recursive\" option argument (e.g. \u001b[1m-o rbind,ro=recursive\u001b[22m). For more details see the \u001b[1mFILESYSTEM-INDEPENDENT MOUNT OPTIONS \u001b[22msection.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 121/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 122/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     Since util-linux 2.31, \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mignores the \u001b[1mbind \u001b[22mflag from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m on a \u001b[1mremount \u001b[22moperation (if \u001b[1m-o remount \u001b[22mis specified on command line). This is necessary to fully control mount options on remount by command line. In previous  versions\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 123/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.027, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     the bind flag has been always applied and it was impossible to re-define mount options without interaction with the bind semantic. This \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mbehavior does not affect situations when \"remount,bind\" is specified in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 124/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.033, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 125/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "     Since util-linux 2.39, \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mmay use the new kernel mount API if it is available. This new kernel interface provides a more precise way to work with mountpoint attributes. For example, the \u001b[1m-o bind,rw \u001b[22moperation will create a read-write\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 126/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     node even if the original node was read-only. This was impossible with the old classic mount(2) syscall, where the read-only VFS flag was inherited from the original node.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 127/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b["]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 128/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b["]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K   \u001b[1mThe move operation\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 129/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     Move a \u001b[1mmounted tree \u001b[22mto another place (atomically). The call is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 130/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 131/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b["]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K        \u001b[1mmount --move \u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 132/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 133/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.028, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "     This will cause the contents which previously appeared under \u001b[4molddir\u001b[24m to now be accessible under \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[24m. The physical location of the files is not changed. Note that \u001b[4molddir\u001b[24m has to be a mountpoint.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 134/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 135/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.284, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     Note also that moving a mount residing under a shared mount is invalid and unsupported. Use \u001b[1mfindmnt -o TARGET,PROPAGATION \u001b[22mto see the current propagation flags.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 136/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.258, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 137/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.032, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "   \u001b[1mShared subtree operations\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 138/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.027, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     Since  Linux  2.6.15 it is possible to mark a mount and its submounts as shared, private, slave or unbindable. A shared mount provides the ability to create mirrors of that mount such that mounts and unmounts within any of the mirrors\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 139/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     propagate to the other mirror. A slave mount receives propagation from its master, but not vice versa. A private mount carries no propagation abilities. An unbindable mount is a private mount which cannot be cloned through a bind  op‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 140/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     eration. The detailed semantics are documented in \u001b[4mDocumentation/filesystems/sharedsubtree.txt\u001b[24m file in the kernel source tree; see also \u001b[1mmount_namespaces\u001b[22m(7).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 141/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[2.240, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 142/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.251, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     Supported operations are:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 143/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 144/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "         mount --make-shared mountpoint\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 145/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "         mount --make-slave mountpoint\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 146/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "         mount --make-private mountpoint\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 147/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "         mount --make-unbindable mountpoint\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 148/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b["]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 149/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b["]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K     The following commands allow one to recursively change the type of all the mounts under a given mountpoint.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 150/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 151/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.036, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "         mount --make-rshared mountpoint\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 152/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "         mount --make-rslave mountpoint\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 153/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "         mount --make-rprivate mountpoint\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 154/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "         mount --make-runbindable mountpoint\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 155/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 156/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     \u001b[1mmount does not read fstab\u001b[22m(5) when a \u001b[1m--make-\u001b[22m* operation is requested. All necessary information has to be specified on the command line.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 157/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 158/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     Note that the Linux kernel does not allow changing multiple propagation flags with a single \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m(2) system call, and the flags cannot be mixed with other mount options and operations.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 159/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 160/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     Since  util-linux  2.23  the \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand can be used to do more propagation (topology) changes by one \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m(8) call and do it also together with other mount operations. The propagation flags are applied by additional \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m(2) system\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 161/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     calls when the preceding mount operations were successful. Note that this use case is not atomic. It is possible to specify the propagation flags in \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) as mount options (\u001b[1mprivate\u001b[22m,  \u001b[1mslave\u001b[22m,  \u001b[1mshared\u001b[22m,  \u001b[1munbindable\u001b[22m,  \u001b[1mrprivate\u001b[22m,  \u001b[1mrslave\u001b[22m,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 162/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.033, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     \u001b[1mrshared\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mrunbindable\u001b[22m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 163/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.033, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 164/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     For example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 165/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 166/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "         mount --make-private --make-unbindable /dev/sda1 /foo\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 167/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 168/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "     is the same as:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 169/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 170/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K         mount /dev/sda1 /foo\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 171/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K         mount --make-private /foo\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 172/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.027, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K         mount --make-unbindable /foo\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 173/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.371, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1mmount -o bind,ro foo foo\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 172/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.259, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b["]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 171/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     Since util-linux 2.27 \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mpermits changing the mount options by passing the relevant options along with \u001b[1m--bind\u001b[22m. For example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 170/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.035, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 169/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     ify the options on the \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand line.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 168/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     Note  that the filesystem mount options maintained by the kernel will remain the same as those on the original mount point. The userspace mount options (e.g., _netdev) will not be copied by \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mand it’s necessary to explicitly spec‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 167/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 166/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1mmount --rbind \u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 165/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 164/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM     The bind mount call attaches only (part of) a single filesystem, not possible submounts. The entire file hierarchy including submounts can be attached a second place by using:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 163/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 162/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1mmount --bind foo foo\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 161/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 160/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     One can also remount a single file (on a single file). It’s also possible to use a bind mount to create a mountpoint from a regular directory, for example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 159/1746 15% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.040, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 158/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     been attached by a \"bind\" operation. The \u001b[4molddir\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[24m are independent and the \u001b[4molddir\u001b[24m may be unmounted.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 157/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     It is important to understand that \"bind\" does not create any second-class or special node in the kernel VFS. The \"bind\" is just another operation to attach a filesystem. There is nowhere stored information  that  the  filesystem  has\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 156/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 155/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     After this call the same contents are accessible in two places.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 154/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 153/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.028, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1m/\u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[1m/\u001b[4m\u001b[22mnewdir\u001b[24m \u001b[1mnone bind\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 152/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 151/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM     or by using this \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m entry:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 150/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 149/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1mmount --bind \u001b[4m\u001b[22molddir\u001b[24m \u001b[4mnewdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 148/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.036, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 147/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM     Remount part of the file hierarchy somewhere else. The call is:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 146/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM   \u001b[1mBind mount operation\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 145/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 144/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     filesystems.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 143/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The  \u001b[1muser  \u001b[22mmount  option  is accepted if no username is specified. If used in the format \u001b[1muser=someone\u001b[22m, the option is silently ignored and visible only for external mount helpers (/sbin/mount.<type>) for compatibility with some network\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 142/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 141/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     user must be a member of the group of the special file.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 140/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     with the restriction that the user must be the owner of the special file. This may be useful e.g. for \u001b[4m/dev/fd\u001b[24m if a login script makes the console user owner of this device. The \u001b[1mgroup \u001b[22moption is similar, with the  restriction  that  the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 139/1746 14% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     For  more details, see \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5). Only the user that mounted a filesystem can unmount it again. If any user should be able to unmount it, then use \u001b[1musers \u001b[22minstead of \u001b[1muser \u001b[22min the \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m line. The \u001b[1mowner \u001b[22moption is similar to the \u001b[1muser \u001b[22moption,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 138/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 137/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.035, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     use-cases where root permissions are not necessary (e.g., fuse filesystems, user namespaces, etc).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 136/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     Since util-linux 2.35, \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mdoes not exit when user permissions are inadequate according to libmount’s internal security rules. Instead, it drops suid permissions and  continues  as  regular  non-root  user.  This  behavior  supports\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 135/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 134/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     tem, otherwise \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mmay fail. For example it’s a bad idea to use NFS or CIFS source on command line.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 133/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     Note  that  \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mis very strict about non-root users and all paths specified on command line are verified before \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m is parsed or a helper program is executed. It’s strongly recommended to use a valid mountpoint to specify filesys‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 132/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 131/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1mmount /cd\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 130/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 129/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     any user can mount the iso9660 filesystem found on an inserted CDROM using the command:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 128/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 127/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1m/dev/cdrom /cd iso9660 ro,user,noauto,unhide\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 126/1746 13% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 125/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     Thus, given a line\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 124/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.027, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 123/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.033, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     Normally, only the superuser can mount filesystems. However, when \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m contains the \u001b[1muser \u001b[22moption on a line, anybody can mount the corresponding filesystem.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 122/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.028, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM   \u001b[1mNon-superuser mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 121/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 120/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     This default behaviour can be changed by using the \u001b[1m--options-source-force \u001b[22mcommand-line option to always read configuration from \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m. For non-root users \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22malways reads the \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m configuration.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 119/1746 12% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 118/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1mmount /dev/foo /dir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 117/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 116/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mprogram does not read the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file if both \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m (or LABEL, UUID, ID, PARTUUID or PARTLABEL) and \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m are specified. For example, to mount device \u001b[1mfoo \u001b[22mat \u001b[1m/dir\u001b[22m:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 115/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.036, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 114/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     wins if there are conflicting ones.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 113/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     and then the mount options from the command line will be appended to the list of options from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m. This default behaviour can be changed using the \u001b[1m--options-mode \u001b[22mcommand-line option. The usual behavior is that the  last  option\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 112/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 111/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[4m\u001b[22mdevice\u001b[24m|\u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m \u001b[1m-o \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptions\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 110/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 109/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     If you want to override mount options from \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m, you have to use the \u001b[1m-o \u001b[22moption:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 108/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 107/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM     If no arguments are given to \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m, the list of mounted filesystems is printed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 106/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 105/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     port is enabled, then it’s possible to use the file as well as the symlink.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 104/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.036, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     Linux systems it is better to make \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m a symlink to \u001b[4m/proc/mounts\u001b[24m instead. The regular \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m file maintained in userspace cannot reliably work with namespaces, containers and other advanced Linux features. If the regular \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m sup‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 103/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.026, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The  programs  \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mand \u001b[1mumount\u001b[22m(8) traditionally maintained a list of currently mounted filesystems in the file \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m. The support for regular classic \u001b[4m/etc/mtab\u001b[24m is completely disabled at compile time by default, because on current\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 102/1746 11% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.032, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 101/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.026, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     When mounting a filesystem mentioned in \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mmtab\u001b[24m, it suffices to specify on the command line only the device, or only the mount point.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 100/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 99/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.033, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     the \u001b[1m-F \u001b[22moption will make \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mfork, so that the filesystems are mounted in parallel.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 98/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     (usually given in a bootscript) causes all filesystems mentioned in \u001b[4mfstab\u001b[24m (of the proper type and/or having or not having the proper options) to be mounted as indicated, except for those whose line contains the \u001b[1mnoauto \u001b[22mkeyword.  Adding\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 97/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 96/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1mmount -a \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-O \u001b[4m\u001b[22moptlist\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 95/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 94/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The command\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 93/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 92/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM     below for more details).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 91/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The  file  \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m (see \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5)), may contain lines describing what devices are usually mounted where, using which options. The default location of the \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) file can be overridden with the \u001b[1m--fstab \u001b[4m\u001b[22mpath\u001b[24m command-line option (see\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 90/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.027, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM   \u001b[1mThe files /etc/fstab, /etc/mtab and /proc/mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 89/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.033, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 88/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     sage 'none already mounted' from \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcan be confusing.)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 87/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The \u001b[4mproc\u001b[24m filesystem is not associated with a special device, and when mounting it, an arbitrary keyword - for example, \u001b[4mproc\u001b[24m - can be used instead of a device specification. (The customary choice \u001b[4mnone\u001b[24m is less fortunate: the error  mes‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 86/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 85/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     udev symlinks, so the use of symlinks in \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m has no advantage over tags. For more details see \u001b[1mlibblkid\u001b[22m(3).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 84/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The  recommended setup is to use tags (e.g. \u001b[1mUUID\u001b[22m=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[24m) rather than \u001b[4m/dev/disk/by-{label,uuid,id,partuuid,partlabel}\u001b[24m udev symlinks in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file. Tags are more readable, robust and portable. The \u001b[1mmount\u001b[22m(8) command internally uses\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 83/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 82/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.033, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     Don’t forget that there is no guarantee that UUIDs and labels are really unique, especially if you move, share or copy the device. Use \u001b[1mlsblk -o +UUID,PARTUUID \u001b[22mto verify that the UUIDs are really unique in your system.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 81/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 80/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The command \u001b[1mlsblk --fs \u001b[22mprovides an overview of filesystems, LABELs and UUIDs on available block devices. The command \u001b[1mblkid -p <device> \u001b[22mprovides details about a filesystem on the specified device.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 79/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 78/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM         udevd is required. This identifier is not recommended for generic use as the identifier is not strictly defined and it depends on udev, udev rules and hardware.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 77/1746 10% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.043, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM         Hardware block device ID as generated by udevd. This identifier is usually based on WWN (unique storage identifier) and assigned by the hardware manufacturer. See \u001b[1mls /dev/disk/by-id \u001b[22mfor more details,  this  directory  and  running\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 76/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.026, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     ID=\u001b[4mid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 75/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 74/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.034, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM         Partition universally unique identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 73/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     PARTUUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 72/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.738, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 71/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.346, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM         Human readable partition identifier. This identifier is independent on filesystem and does not change by \u001b[1mmkfs \u001b[22mor \u001b[1mmkswap \u001b[22moperations. It’s supported for example for GUID Partition Tables (GPT).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 70/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.236, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     PARTLABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 69/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.251, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 68/1746 9% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[1.347, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM         Note that \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22muses UUIDs as strings. The UUIDs from the command line or from \u001b[1mfstab\u001b[22m(5) are not converted to internal binary representation. The string representation of the UUID should be based on lower case characters.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 67/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.256, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 66/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM         Filesystem universally unique identifier. The format of the UUID is usually a series of hex digits separated by hyphens. See also \u001b[1m-U\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 65/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     UUID=\u001b[4muuid\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 64/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 63/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM         Human readable filesystem identifier. See also \u001b[1m-L\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 62/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     LABEL=\u001b[4mlabel\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 61/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 60/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.041, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     UUID or LABEL. Currently supported identifiers (tags):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 59/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The  device  names of disk partitions are unstable; hardware reconfiguration, and adding or removing a device can cause changes in names. This is the reason why it’s strongly recommended to use filesystem or partition identifiers like\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 58/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 57/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     Most devices are indicated by a filename (of a block special device), like \u001b[4m/dev/sda1\u001b[24m, but there are other possibilities. For example, in the case of an NFS mount, \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m may look like \u001b[4mknuth.cwi.nl:/dir\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 56/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM   \u001b[1mIndicating the device and filesystem\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 55/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 54/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The option \u001b[1m-l \u001b[22madds labels to this listing. See below.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 53/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 52/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.029, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22m[\u001b[1m-l\u001b[22m] [\u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 51/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 50/1746 8% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The following command lists all mounted filesystems (of type \u001b[4mtype\u001b[24m):\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 49/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.035, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 48/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     For more robust and customizable output use \u001b[1mfindmnt\u001b[22m(8), \u001b[1mespecially in your scripts\u001b[22m. Note that control characters in the mountpoint name are replaced with '?'.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 47/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 46/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The listing mode is maintained for backward compatibility only.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 45/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM   \u001b[1mListing the mounts\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 44/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 43/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     behavior. All behavior is controlled by the kernel and it is usually specific to the filesystem driver. The exception is \u001b[1m--all\u001b[22m, in this case already mounted filesystems are ignored (see \u001b[1m--all \u001b[22mbelow for more details).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 42/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.031, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The same filesystem may be mounted more than once, and in some cases (e.g., network filesystems) the same filesystem may be mounted on the same mountpoint multiple times. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand does not implement any policy to control this\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 41/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.028, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 40/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1mmount --target \u001b[4m\u001b[22m/mountpoint\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 39/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 38/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.037, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     then \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mlooks for a mountpoint (and if not found then for a device) in the \u001b[4m/etc/fstab\u001b[24m file. It’s possible to use the \u001b[1m--target \u001b[22mor \u001b[1m--source \u001b[22moptions to avoid ambiguous interpretation of the given argument. For example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 37/1746 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 36/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1mmount \u001b[4m\u001b[22m/dir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 35/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.027, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 34/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     If only the directory or the device is given, for example:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 33/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.033, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 32/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     refers to the root of the filesystem on \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 31/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     to mount a filesystem by default. See section \"Non-superuser mounts\" below for more details. The previous contents (if any) and owner and mode of \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m become invisible, and as long as this filesystem remains mounted, the  pathname  \u001b[4mdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 30/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.026, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     This  tells the kernel to attach the filesystem found on \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m (which is of type \u001b[4mtype\u001b[24m) at the directory \u001b[4mdir\u001b[24m. The option \u001b[1m-t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m is optional. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand is usually able to detect a filesystem. The root permissions are necessary\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 29/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 28/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.034, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM        \u001b[1mmount -t \u001b[4m\u001b[22mtype\u001b[24m \u001b[4mdevice\u001b[24m \u001b[4mdir\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 27/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 26/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     The standard form of the \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand is:\u001b[m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 25/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 24/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.027, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     file tree. Conversely, the \u001b[1mumount\u001b[22m(8) command will detach it again. The filesystem is used to control how data is stored on the device or provided in a virtual way by network or other services.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 23/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.033, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM     All files accessible in a Unix system are arranged in one big tree, the file hierarchy, rooted at \u001b[4m/\u001b[24m. These files can be spread out over several devices. The \u001b[1mmount \u001b[22mcommand serves to attach the filesystem found on some device to the big\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 22/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.347, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 21/1746 6% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.257, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bM\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[67;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[01;44;33m Manual page mount(8) line 20/1746 5% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[0m\u001b[K"]
[0.030, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[K[\b[\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K"]
